      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 54-year-old man with a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is admitted to the hospital for worsening shortness of breath. During his stay, he develops sudden onset confusion and ataxia. The medical team suspects a neurological issue secondary to his respiratory condition. They consider the potential role of trace elements in his new neurological symptoms. To guide their differential diagnosis, one of the team members asks.&nbsp;</span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Which of the following enzymes, potentially relevant to this patient&#39;s new neurological symptoms, does not require copper as a cofactor?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5467416",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30595,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D) Glutathione peroxidase </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Glutathione peroxidase </strong>is an enzyme that contains <strong>selenium as a cofactor, </strong>not copper. It plays a crucial role in the <strong>reduction </strong>of <strong>peroxides</strong>, <strong>protecting </strong>the cell from <strong>oxidative damage </strong>by <strong>reducing lipid hydroperoxides </strong>to their corresponding <strong>alcohols and reducing free hydrogen peroxide </strong>to<strong> water</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Lysyl oxidase</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: <strong>Incorrect </strong>because <strong>lysyl oxidase</strong>, which is involved in the <strong>cross-linking </strong>of <strong>collagen and elastin</strong>, does contain <strong>copper as a cofactor.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Cytochrome oxidase</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: <strong>Incorrect </strong>as <strong>cytochrome oxidase</strong>, a key enzyme in the <strong>mitochondrial electron transport </strong>chain responsible for the<strong> final step </strong>in <strong>cellular respiration</strong>, also <strong>contains copper</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Dopamine &beta;-hydroxylase</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: <strong>Incorrect </strong>because <strong>dopamine &beta;-hydroxylase, </strong>which converts <strong>dopamine to norepinephrine</strong>, is another <strong>copper-containing enzyme</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Glutathione peroxidase (GP) </strong>is the important <strong>selenium </strong>containing enzyme.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Copper </strong>containing enzymes include <strong>Lysyl oxidase, Cytochrome oxidase, Dopamine hydroxylase </strong>and <strong>superoxide dismutase.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: p 234, 721.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
